We also envisage sharing some of our methodolgical findings with the AGT, as part of their ongoing care of the historical object on which the project has focused, and these findings may form part of the project's wider knoweldge transfer aspect, if conservators currently working on the project are able to transfer skills, practices and findings gained on the project to their other work (e.g., for local museums such as Exeter's Royal Albert Memorial Museum).

Another outcome of the project will a media archive, including interactive webpages, virtual replica and short documentary film. These will be available to visitors to the AGT at the project's conclusion, as well as to anyone visiting the project's site while it is hosted by the University of Exeter, and the film may be screened as part of a public showcase of the project's work.

A physical replica of the Eureka Latin Verse Machine will have been constructed by the end of the project, which can be exhibited publically.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>B2A497D7-4AAD-40C0-A264-251B112053AE</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Discovered more exactly the functioning of the Eureka Latin Verse Machine and the principles on which it was orginally constructed.

